i’ve been rereading a lot of bell hooks this past year. Her book, Art On My Mind: Visual Politics, is currently in my rotation again. A lot of her writings in this text remind me of my experiences with white feminism, respectability, white supremacy, and capitalism as a food-based designer and artist. These things have been a pain as a Black woman straddling the fence between the culinary and art worlds. 

Here are some of my favorite quotes from the text w/ images of Theaster Gates work from the exhibit, A Movement in Every Direction: Legacies of the Great Migration. Sit with these words for a bit, especially if you’re a Black person in food or art.

"Throughout the history of postslavery African-American art making, class hierarchies both within and outside black communities have shaped the nature of art practices, controlling the way art by African-American artists is critically considered. The standards of valuation used in white-dominated art circles were and often still are applied in segregated black culture. As a consequence, the black poor and working-class did not and do not have a primary voice in shaping black aesthetics. Even when Black liberation movements of the 1960s and early 1970s extolled the virtues of laboring classes, the folks who defined what our relationship to art and aesthetics should be were still primarily the black bourgeoisie."

"Since most black folks in the United States are colonized--that is think about "blackness" in much the same ways as racist white mainstream culture--simply being a black female artist does not mean one possess the vision and insight to create groundbreaking revolutionary images of black females.”

(Speaking here to Carrie Mae Weems) “I disagree with one of the critics who said that your work "takes us beyond abstract ideas." I thought, actually, no, her work takes us to the abstract complexity within black identity that has been denied, and that has been denied not merely by politics of race but by politics of culture, and particularly that of vernacular culture in opposition to high culture. In part as a response to high culture's attempt to reduce vernacular culture in your work, in the images."

New Year’s Day Cassoulet with Sea Island Peas, Carolina Gold Rice, and Tea Smoked Greens. To me, making cassoulet always feels like the best dish to welcome the new year. Traditionally, cassoulet uses a lot of duck, but i like to honor my tradition of eating pork for New Year’s by using Ham Hocks and Pork Shoulder instead of the traditionally used sausages and duck confit. The time it takes to prep and cook makes cassoulet one of those dishes that align perfectly with this season of intention setting. I served the pork and peas with rice and greens braised in a lapsang souchong (smoked black tea) chicken broth and seasoned with @nomaprojects Smoked Mushroom Garum. Oh, and instead of using regular breadcrumbs on top of my cassoulet, i used skillet cornbread crumbs because you can’t have new year’s peas and greens without cornbread! With all the talk of low vibration plates in 2022, i know more and more folks are eating less pork these days, but eating it on New Year’s is my way of honoring the choices my ancestors made to survive; choices i’ll forever be thankful for. Happy Jordan year everyone ✨
In 2023 i continue to continue 🏴‍☠️

Wow. It’s an honor to share that i’m a 2023 United States Artists Architecture & Design Fellow. It is even more of an honor to be the first artist or designer in the history of the USA Fellowship that mostly works with food! Thank you to whoever nominated me & thanks to the United States Artists organization for the support. i am grateful for the opportunity to name my work and continue to publicly claim my space as a food designer and social practice artist.

i approach food, design, and art as the cultural practices they have been and continue to become outside of the institutional framework and gaze of the mainstream culinary, fine art, & design worlds, so to receive this nomination and then award from a national arts organization & judges working in the design world was completely unexpected. But trust me, i am so proud & thankful. i was nominated in traditional arts but tapped into the spirit of Octavia Butler and wrote myself into Architecture & Design, making this even more special bc i was able to name myself & my work.

My art and design practice are VERY MUCH for me and the life i lead as an able-presenting disabled Black woman from Baltimore. However, as i pour into my cup, it continues to become more apparent to me that what “runneth over,” so to speak, is connecting with others also questioning their colonized relationships to food, nature, and other human beings.

Thank you to all my past and present patreon patrons who have supported my livelihood over the past four years. @_mattfreire thank you for giving me the time and space to create! To Sharea Harris (@sharea_rea) and Alexis Dixon, thank you for your support and care on this journey! It feels surreal to be on a list that has previously honored so many who's work i deeply respect and regularly engage with. Kiese Laymon. Ocean Vuong. Simone Leigh. Greg Tate. Alexander Chee. Sonya Clark. Theaster Gates. Cauleen Smith. Claudia Rankine. Lorraine O’Grady. It's honestly too many to list.

i have so much more to say about this award but deadlines have me swamped. For now, swipe for all my internet sourced feelings and click the link in my bio for the full list of USA Fellows 🫶🏾 ID soon in comments.

Hopping online to add my current hyper-fixation with ramps (wild garlic) to the many ramp photos & videos likely already on your feed this spring. As i sit & began to draft a caption to these slides i realize that this, cooking & posting the end result online, is what many think that i do and that’s it. 

Most artists working with food or at least the ones that are food adjacent are often known as performance artists. They make food for the masses. The food is good but the way in which the food is shared is a class spectacle that pushes them into the forefront. The setting is untraditional or the artist themselves is some kind of unique character that makes something as simple as eating fruit or curry a transformational experience. But oftentimes it is that type of performance that makes me cringe. 

The more the performance around food is centered (in America) the more i cringe because it does not feel honest. The food web, seasonality, labor, accessibility, food waste, and time are often disregarded in food performance and it’s positioned as a romanticized form of cooking. It feels like careless….maybe even dangerous design. And so, i tend to not dabble in food performance because more often than not it feels tone deaf and unsustainable. 

However, because of this, i understand that leaves many of you confused about my practice. i am not doing the dinners.  i don’t have a restaurant. i don’t “pop-up”. i don’t often partner with luxury brands as a influencer. i don’t rock designer attire while making *insert random french pastry dish*.

i forage & garden. i write. i cook in t-shirts & sweats for my loved ones & myself. i research & study. For many reasons, that very personal “performance” is no easy effort for me. But that quiet performance of living, while not glamorous & marketable (2 things necessary for financial & social survival in mainstream food & art), is the way i choose to engage with an art form (cooking) & material (food) that keeps us alive physically, spiritually, & culturally. And honestly, maybe that personal, quiet performance in a food & art world that is so loud IS the most prized performance. Anyway, image descriptions in the comments 🌱💛

Excited to partner with @advaya.co by sharing their latest offering, Sensing Harm by Design 💫

Created and facilitated by arts and research collective Gesturing Towards Decolonial Futures, this six-week course is designed to support you to activate dispositions that can expand your capacity to navigate increasing volatility, uncertainty, complexity, and ambiguity (VUCA).

In response to the current modern-colonial system that requires harm by design, this course offers a container and methodology for interrupting patterns, letting go of harmful attachments and co-dependence with the system itself, and committing to a process of cognitive, affective, and relational “decluttering”—as a CONTINUOUS PRACTICE.

Through this course you will feel better equipped to navigate complexities, uncertainties, and complicities, becoming more motivated to do difficult work. This includes the work of building relationships rooted in trust, respect, reciprocity, consent, and accountability.

This course would be a GREAT investment of time and resources for folks working in the food or art scene who are looking to incorporate these skills into their practice and community building efforts.

Sensing Harm by Design runs from June 26th to July 31st (Mondays from 5-7 pm UK/12-2pm EST). Meet me there and use KRYSTAL20 for 20% off General Admission tickets. Click the link in my bio to register today 🚀

Yesterday was Autistic Pride Day and today is Juneteenth so i’ve been pouring libation with this Bissap Spritz all weekend and honoring myself by being honest about my capacity and needs. i tend to be pretty good at this in my work life but i have a hard time extending this care to my personal life as an Autistic Black woman. 

When living in the freedom of my truth around care and needs as a Black Autistic woman, with the exception of my disabled Black friends, i find that this often positions me as an outsider in the Black community. 

As i continue on my decolonization journey, the struggle to honor my truth and let go of the toxic things that served me as a younger person (like ABA therapies for example) is too real. It’s especially hard in a society that is inherently racist, ableist, homophobic, capitalist, and sexist. It’s hard enough dealing with this from white people but the pain of ableism, sexism, homophobia, and classism from folks who have a intimate knowledge of the shared oppression we face as Black and Brown people is a wild and daily mind-fuck. 

So much of what has been normalized as a healthy way of communicating and being in community with one another as Black people under white supremacy and it’s byproducts are some of the things that keeps us from decolonizing and claiming our freedom. Freedom, which is more of a journey and way of being than it is a destination.

There is no Black freedom without the freedom of, love of, inclusion of, and investment in all Black people. INCLUDING DISABLED BLACK FOLKS.

So yesterday, today, and everyday i honor my Black disabled ancestors (like Harriet Tubman, a disabled Black woman like many of our enslaved ancestors by the way) for the sacrifices that they made for so many of us. Sacrifices that have been erased by white folk and our own people to serve a white supremacist ideology of ableist Black excellence. Thank you for planting the seeds for our freedom. i pray we find the love that is needed for us to truly harvest its abundance some day 🖤🌺 ID in alt text and the comments.

This recipe touches on pillar three of my Five Pillars of a New Diasporic Comestible Practice (Recipe Engineering, Research, and Documentation). Recipe Engineering is essentially culinary remixing and sampling in the spirit of Sankofa. 

Just as music engineers use audio tools and software to capture sound, recipe engineering utilizes traditional and ancestral culinary methods, diasporic heirloom ingredients, and migratory cultural exchange to capture a story through food. Viewing a recipe as a sensory time capsule, recipe engineering evokes jazz and hip-hop’s rhythmic and improvisational spirit, telling the varied narratives of individuals with blood ties to the continent. 

This recipe as well as an Elder plant profile from last year and my “Five Pillars of a New Diasporic Comestible Practice” can be found on my Patreon (link in bio)! Your support helps keep my process sustainable 🤍 #ScheduledPost

Here’s some process footage of a summer ‘22 jam from my comestible archive,✨Wineberry & Red Currant Jam with @diasporaco Paneer Rose✨ 

These wildforaged wineberries were being choked out by ivy last year when i came across them. After cutting back a large amount of the invasive vines, i gathered some berries and archived them into a jam. After coming back to the same forest patch this year, many of the wineberry bushes were dead. They appear to have been strangled by the ivy. So pulling from the archive to have this jam for breakfast hits different this summer 💔

There are so many ways for one to archive. For me, this looks like wild food preservation, organically reduced indigo vats, compost transmutation, and more. Comestible Archiving is a category of food design i’ve developed to describe the archival work i’ve created over the years as a food designer. Food design in my practice is largely about the creation or expansion of processes and systems that balance contemporary stewardship with consumption, while unpacking the personal and collective traumas that tip those scales. The ephemeral nature of this archive allows one to revisit sensory memories of the past, recontextualizing the joy and grief that comes with nuances of time and ecological change. This jam from last year embodies the value of this work and what can be lost when we turn our backs on the more-than-human world.

While the methods i use to archive the emotional seasons of humanity and the environmental seasons in nature have existed for centuries in indigenous communities around the world, presenting and documenting these methods as a form of food-based sociology and decolonization is a newer approach in the fields of contemporary art and design. More of my comestible archiving research can be found on my Patreon (link in bio) ☝🏾

i don’t typically post about restaurants but i want to talk about @littledonnas. 

The food is delicious. 👌🏾

They know what they are doing and the space and energy of everyone there is so sincere and unforced. We need more restaurants with genuine hospitality that care about their menus being honestly celebrated in Bmore. This is my attempt at that lol. i was so busy enjoying my meal that i didn’t snap any photos but standout of the night when i visited was the soft shell crab pizza with green tomato & smoky aioli. i finished off my meal with the Flor de Luna Pineapple & Chili Amaro. 

It’s really refreshing to go to a cute newer restaurant in Baltimore where they are in the business of feeding people delicious and fun food and not just overcharging you to be in their cute space while eating bland food. 

Good food when dining out shouldn’t be a novel thing. Dear Baltimore restaurants and cafes, you can do both! Little Donna’s is proof of that. Cute design of a food space builds a brand but thoughtful menu design and ambiance build a solid restaurant or cafe. 

i don’t post about restaurants in Baltimore for many reasons but one reason is because the food is often a miss and weirdly expensive for the average income of a Baltimorean (especially these days). If i had to sum up what my general experience has been dining out in my hometown lately it would be that clip of Aretha Franklin (SWIPE) saying “okayyy….great gowns….beautiful gowns.” When i see top lists of new restaurants here my energy towards the options have me feeling like Aretha on Taylor. 

In recent years we’ve had a slew of new bars, restaurants, and cafes open up in Baltimore that are gorgeous and fun on the inside but the menu is an overpriced afterthought. i had this experience just yesterday getting lunch with a friend. Even the places that used to be solid have gone down in quality in order to scale up to meet demand. With the exception of pop ups and a handful of fine dining spots, dining out in Central Baltimore can be an expensive disappointment. 

But Little Donna’s did not disappoint and running a restaurant is really hard so let’s give them the business they deserve 💛

If you’re in the Baltimore area, join Alicia and i next month for a conversation at @redemmas! We’ll chat about diets as a form of resistance, tech meat startups, and the co-opting of plant-based cooking by the Wellness™ movement among many other things. Click the link in my story to grab yourself a copy ✌🏾

Surprise books in the mail from @klancycooks 🥰 What i love about this gift is that i’ve quietly wanted to read both of these and like magic they manifested in the mail. i love Samantha Irby and now have all of her books! i’m not a big fiction reader, but i’ve wanted to pick up Yellowface. It's been challenging to get through this one. It reminds me of my observations and fringe experiences with food media/publishing. These include but aren't limited to white saviors, the performance and toxicity of social media, cultural appropriation, surface-level attempts at DEI, and the competitive and white supremacist view that “there can only be one” that Black and Brown folks often inflict on each other. It's a stressful read for me, like The Bear is a stressful watch for me. Good, but stressful. 😅 Let me know your thoughts if you've read or are reading these! And if you have book suggestions, leave them in the comments! 🤓📚

“On her first day, Elsie got an eyeful. It was 1947. She was thirty-three years old. That day, she heard laughter and looked outside to see the Kaufmanns and their guests as they splashed and frolicked in the chilly waters. Nude. “I was standing there at the stove, and there were ten or twelve people—all buck naked—under the falls. It was a mixed crowd (men and women), and some of them were on their backs. I thought, ‘It’s a nudist camp!’

“What have I gotten myself into?” she wondered. What she had gotten into turned out to be the highlight of her culinary career.” -The Fallingwater Cookbook: Elsie Henderson’s Recipes & Memories

When i went to Fallingwater a few weeks back i was so happy to learn about Ms. Henderson (big thank you to our tour guide Thomas), and see Fallingwater through the eyes of a Black woman. It was also interesting to learn about her relationship with the Kaufmanns, the owners of Fallingwater. When i go to cultural sites in our country i often wonder what it would have been like for me if i was in the space as a Black woman at the height of it’s use. Because of forgotten or erased histories, i often just have to wonder. But her perspective is so insightful. It’s disappointing that the draw of the Fallingwater cookbook and a large chunk of it’s contents are Elsie’s  anecdotes and recipes, yet she was not credited as an author or owner to the rights to her own lived experience. Disappointing but not surprising. Three authors and none of them her…..we’ve come a long way, but we still have so much further to go. Elsie Henderson passed away last spring at the age of 107.

i was recently part of a publishing project that has allowed me to see a larger through line in my work: dignity & restoration through creation. i try to approach what i create cautiously & with intention. This is especially true when creating work that uses the narratives or experiences of others.  An example of this i am most proud of are the interviews i conducted for my newsprint @palatePALETTE.co. 

Because i understand the role published work plays in encapsulating one’s work & identity, it was important to me that folks were featured with dignity. Being an Autistic Black woman survivor from Baltimore, dignity in the media is deeply important to me. i list those identities because, in the media, folks with them or at their intersections often have their narratives & experiences erased, mishandled, tokenized, or misappropriated. i’ve seen it happen to folks dear to me & in recent years, have been subjected to this by publications & people i’ve long admired.

In creating palatePALETTE, i sought restoration for my problematic experiences with the media by giving the folks featured what i & many others do not get in that field: DIGNITY. i interviewed folks whose work tends to be celebrated as a novelty or given limited context when featured. With the newsprint, i wanted to counter that surface approach. The questions were unique to each interviewee, allowing for a more personal context to honor their humanity. It was also important to me that the interviews were published in the native language & dialects of those speaking. i worked with international translators to get the interviews printed in regional dialects of Syrian Arabic, West African French, & good old Baltimore English because i believe it extractive to have an interview published that you can’t read, is not in your voice/dialect, poorly edited, or chaotically incoherent. With every literary work, my understanding of the art and power of the interview format has deepened. So, too, has my understanding of support, aftercare, & one’s relationship with their interviewees & editor. All of these are things that make the process of publishing narratives invaluable. Cooking. Medicine-making. Foraging. Dyeing. These are some ways i expand my relationship with the forest. They are also the ways i share what i continue to learn about being in right relationship with the more-than-human world. This summer i wrapped up my year as an artist in residence with the @u.s.forestservice x @the_nature_of_cities Urban Field Station Collaborative Arts Program! It was an honor to be the first Baltimore UFS AiR and connect with scientists, researchers, and organizers in the Greater Chesapeake region and beyond.  This residency has significantly shaped my practice and helped lay the foundation for how i will publicly share my work for years to come. 

i’m thrilled to be sharing a bit more about my Comestible Archiving work next week during the World Forum on Urban Forests! Join me, @Nikki.Lindt, @MaryMattingly, and @MattLopezJensen, on Monday October 16th at the @DCPublicLibrary MLK branch for an interactive session called “The Multi-Sensory Urban Forest: Many Ways of Knowing, Sensing, and Caring.” Each of us will be sharing work that engages sight, sound, taste, touch, and smell of urban forests to gain a deeper understanding of ourselves in relation to urban ecosystems. 

i will be doing a meditative indigo dyeing demo in the rooftop garden and sharing how i collaborate with forest patches in Baltimore and beyond for the comestible archiving element of my social practice. This event is FREE and open to the public. Click the link in my bio to register! There is metered street parking in front of the libraryand the roof as well as the rest of the library is wheelchair accessible.

Four residencies in New York City (2) and at Hubbard Brook Experimental Forest (2), one residency position at the Baltimore Field Station, and four residency positions available in any of the following cities: Detroit, Boston, Minneapolis/St. Paul, Milwaukee, St. Louis, Chicago. Click the link in my bio to apply!!

As a Black American and 2nd gen descendant of The Great Migration, i see the threads of connection between the experiences of Black American descendants of enslaved Africans and the Palestinian experience. The bombing of Palestinian homes and mosques brings to mind the bombings of Black homes and churches in the American South. To quote June Jordan, “I was born a Black woman, and now I become a Palestinian……” State-empowered historical and cultural amnesia would like us to think otherwise, but freedom for Palestine is freedom for us all. It is time for us to create new means and ways of understanding what Black elders and ancestors have been trying to teach us for so long: that our struggle here in the states is part of a larger decolonial struggle.

In this process, i continue to educate myself by reading, listening, witnessing, and taking action offline. However, this, too, is a space where action should be taken. As artists, chefs, entrepreneurs, restaurateurs, farmers, organizers, and interdisciplinary creatives with platforms, it’s time our praxis directly reflected that if it does not already. It DOES NOT go without saying, and our words should be in alignment with our actions. 

i am proud of folks from all walks in Baltimore for organizing to support the liberation of Palestine. @redemmas has created a digital zine (link in bio) as an educational resource on the history of Palestine inspired by the work of @decolonizepalestine.  @motzi.bread and @geninselections are partnering on a bread & wine fundraiser for @palestinianmedicalreliefsoc. 

As i continue to do my part offline, i am looking for 2-4 Baltimore herbalists to aid me in that work—please DM, email, or text for more details. I STAND IN SOLIDARITY WITH PALESTINE 🖤 🇵🇸

Full body for the alg because y’all know i don’t do this. Sharing more June Jordan and a gentle reminder to call your reps and demand a ceasefire 🇵🇸🍉🗝️ The poem is “Apologies to All the People in Lebanon” by June Jordan. She dedicated this poem to the 600,000 Palestinian men, women, and children who lived in Lebanon from 1948-1983. This book, “Living Room: New Poems” was published in 1984.

The first real cold nights are upon us. As we prepare for less daylight and inch closer towards winter, it feels like the right time to share some herbal medicine in the form of my Potlicker Fire Cider with my dear patrons on @Patreon. i created this recipe a few years back to honor the ritual of cooking greens in the colder months as well as the folkloric beauty of Black American herbalism. This medicine is full of anti-viral and anti-inflammatory ingredients to help support the immune system. In times like these when the world is rife with pain and suffering, it's important to remember that caring for our bodies is resistance as well ✊🏾🖤

Recipe is in your inbox if you’re a @patreon subscriber 📮

FREE HERBAL CARE PACKAGES FOR PALESTINIANS IN EXILE 🗝️🍉

In times like these, it’s easy for so many of us to turn to donations and fundraisers to support humanitarian aid efforts. But with aid being withheld or destroyed in Gaza, i began to think of ways to show up for Palestinian folk here in the US. Along with listening, learning, boycotts, protests, and calling our congressman i realized i really wanted to share plant medicine with folks who are in exile in the states because caring for our bodies is also resistance. As i share in the above announcement, plants are there as a witness and ally in our times of celebration and grief so it felt right to collaborate with plants and medicine makers on Piscataway land for a reparative offering that aids in resistance!

For the past month i’ve been DM-ing and emailing folks across Baltimore to organize an equity-based care offering to distribute and it’s finally ready! So grateful to everyone in Baltimore for answering my call for community herbal care. THANK YOU TO MY @PATREON PATRONS FOR HELPING FUND THIS WORK! Thank you to my dear care package co-conspirators @juniperbone, @aylenvioleta (@rukahealinghouse ) and Paul (@nineofcupsherbs ) of @nonameplantcollective, @juniperbaltimore, and @bwillowbmo! Thank you to @freebaltimoreyoga for supporting our care efforts with medicine packaging! 

An especially big deep and beautiful thank you to my beloved friend @aisha_alfadhalah for translating our offering announcement! Thank you for always showing up and being so encouraging ❤️🥲

If you are a Palestinian in exile in the United States who would like to receive a care package, sign up by clicking the link in my bio. Packages are limited and will ship out the end of next week!

Look for the algo (bc sadly this strategy is working?) to boost awareness of the BRILLIANT @lalph_rauren. We connected in 2021 thanks to a misleading and virtue-signaling IG post from NY-based food artists lev.nyc. Our conversation changed so much about how i approach my work with the more-than-human world.  As a labor of love & community, Amanny seeded in me the sacred kinship 🇵🇸 have with olive trees & the significance of this relationship in the fight for the liberation of 🇵🇸 people.

Over the past 2 years, because of Amanny, i’ve continued to read up on the olive tree, its power as a symbol for freedom, & the 🫒’s importance as a foodway. In my studies, i’ve researched the energetic qualities of the olive tree as a companion in land stewardship, as well as the medicinal properties of olive leaves. This work of nurturing the seed that Amanny planted led to the creation of Solidarity, an Olive Leaf, Mallow, & Lemongrass tisane from my comestible archive that i am sharing with 🇵🇸 folks in the @iao.studio care packages.

Thank you for for seeding in me the creation of this tea Amanny. When looking to people who inspire my work, the only woman artist working with food i’ve consistently pointed to IS Amanny. She stands 10 toes down unapologetically in her work & it is refreshing to know that there are folks like her FEEDING THE TRUTH in all the ways one can. It makes one feel seen & sane to know their are folks like her in a food & art world that often feels like scenes from Bamboozled or Get Out. @lalph_rauren , thank you challenging me as an artist & Black American woman with patience & love. This offering exists because of your dedication to liberation, your continued honesty, & vulnerability. 3 things some of y’alls faves often weaponize against Black & Brown women like us in food & art 🥱 Grateful to be creating alongside you Amanny & thankful we can grow in community together ❤️

Flashing back this Friday to my last public event in October (The Multi-Sensory Urban Forest: Many Ways of Knowing, Sensing, and Caring”) where i did a meditative indigo demonstration at the @dcpubliclibrary during the #WorldForumOnUrbanForests2023! i was able to share my comestible archiving practice with foresters from around the world. 

i did an indigo dyeing demo with my pawpaw and date fruit indigo vats while talking about ways urban foresters, municipalities, and organizations around the globe could create sustainable comestible and artisan economies by planting native fruit trees. By doing so folks could potentially feed communities while fostering small-scale circular organic dye practices! 

i also shared a triptych of tisanes for attendees to smell from my archiving of Springfield Woods, a forest patch in northeast Baltimore City full of beautiful and inspiring Black history. Each fragrant tisane exists as a comestible portrait of this urban forest throughout the seasons with wild foraged nettle in the spring, wild foraged sassafrass in the summer, and wild foraged shiso in the fall. The archiving of this forest took place from summer 2022 to summer 2023 and i sent the attendees home with the fall tisane portrait (a shiso chai with spicebush and long pepper, warming and floral with a hint of cacao on the nose) that i was able to archive few weeks before the event)! 

It was such a beautiful experience to be able offer a literal taste of Baltimore to folks from around the world. Thank you to the @u.s.forestservice and the @the_nature_of_cities for the opportunity to do so. Still gives me a happy buzzy feeling just thinking about it! More on this coming to Patreon next week. Click the link in the bio to support the sustainable continuation of my work! 🤗💓

Flashing back this Friday with a look from Christmas brunch last year to share photos from our time in Utah. It’s always a culture shock for me when we go to Utah but it’s also a nice and necessary reminder of the very different lives folks lead in our country. 

We drove from Salt Lake City to Cedar City in southern Utah this year and i was able to take in the mountains and finally (i think) perfect my In and Out Burger order (cheeseburger mustard grilled with extra raw onions and pickles a medium light fry and a Dr. Pepper)!

Some interesting things i wanted to share about the bars and restaurants: most bars shut down at midnight in Salt Lake and UT state law requires establishments that serve alcohol to have their staff wear name tags. My knee jerk reaction to the presence of name tags in fine dining and bar spaces was “how odd” BUT i guess that is kind of a nice way to keep guest from being presented with a not-so-safe mystery drink from someone posing as staff? One could also argue that the tags humanize folks beyond the “Miss” and “Sir” even though the tags can be hideous to owners who care about the aesthetics of staff with their business. All of the bottle shops are state-owned and they also scan your ID to enter bars/when you order drinks which was a unique experience that lost its novelty by day five 😁

Interesting observations were made and characters met on our journey. A smidge about the pup in the last photos and our interaction with her older Australian owner who “broke her” is on my Patreon.

All in all Utah this time around was fascinating as always. In a state where the culture of ⚪️ness, conservativeness, and religion has shaped what folks offer as well as when and where, it was interesting to see some attempt to create progressive change with the little design choices they make as business owners and creatives.
